name: HARRY SPENCE
text:
A MONEY GRUBBING BUNCH,  THEY EMPLOY A DOG CATCHER POSING AS A BUILDING INSPECTOR.  HERE IS WHAT COOSA VALLEY ELECTRICT COOP SAYS ABOUT THIS GUY.
EVIDENTIALLY EMPLOYEE WHITE BRINGS DISGRACE ON THIS TOWN ALONG WITH THE FAAILED MAYOR.

By CHRIS NORWOOD, Home staff Writer : " Coosa Valley Electrical Cooperative spokesman Jon Cullimore said the company takes exception to remarks made Tuesday by Lincoln city building inspector Chris White. During a work session Tuesday, White said that CVEC had expressed appreciation for the city conducting safety inspections in its police jurisdiction before allowing power hookups. “He made the statement that we were grateful for the city’s help,” Cullimore said. “We disagree. We have our own safety inspection processes, and we have been doing this for more than 75 years now. "Our engineers know the requirements under the National Electric Code (which governs the line from the pole to the meter) and the National Electric Safety Code (which covers the meter to the residence or business).”

name: Google Mapper
text:
Pleasantly surprised. The City Hall staff were nice, friendly, and helpful. Plus, the facility was beautiful. Although, not as beautiful as the Court Clerk! They require a face mask and social distancing is well planned and posted. I was expecting more of the urban "city worker" attitude and hearing numerous phones ringing in the background that go unattended. You know, where one clerk window is open with 20+ people in line. While four other windows are closed because those clerks ate watching TikTok on their phone. You've been there before. Not in New Hope Alabama. New Hope City Hall is professional and proficient. They are what all other city buildings in this country should strive to be!!!! Well done and a special thanks to the Sheriff's office for helping as well. Experience = memorable.
( **No, I have never been there before, don't know anyone who works there, not a resident, and not getting paid to write this post!!)

name: Jesse Jasnoch
text:
I visited Blue Springs State Park on January 2nd- at like 8:30AM...Not optimal for most folks.

However, it only cost me $3 to get in and I had the park entirely to myself. The Blue Springs were beautiful and the water was crystal clear. I had a great time taking pictures, walking slow, and breathing in the fresh air. The staff at the front gate were REALLY nice as well!

Plenty of stuff to do for all: Camping, Fishing, Wading in the Springs, Paddle Boats, Picnicking, Walking, Play Ground for the Kiddos and I think I saw a Volleyball net too.

BTW: Right across the street is Hagler's Bar-B-Que. Its Awesome too!

Good Talk,
JJ
